 cashes in on chances\"] at thewest.com.au\n*[http://sbl.asn.au/2018/07/05/parsons-excited-by-hawks-future-having-fought-through-tough-times/ \"Parsons excited by Hawks future having fought through tough times\"] at sbl.asn.au\n*[http://www.hawksbasketball.com.au/ben-purser-300-games/ \"Ben Purser 300 Games\"] at hawksbasketball.com.au\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purser, Ben}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Augusta Jaguars men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Australian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Christ Church Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Perth Wildcats players]]\n", "name_user": "DaHuzyBru", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAll-Defensive pedigree and quarter-final losses (2015\u201317):consistency", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Purser"}
{"title_page": "Loving v. Virginia", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S. Supreme Court case abolishing restrictions on interracial marriage}} Rosa parks\n{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n| Litigants = Loving v. Virginia\n| ArgueDate = April 10\n| ArgueYear = 1967\n| DecideDate = June 12\n| DecideYear = 1967\n| FullName = Richard Perry Loving, Mildred Jeter Loving v. Virginia\n| USVol = 388\n| USPage = 1\n| ParallelCitations = 87 S. Ct. 1817; 18 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 1010; 1967 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1082\n| Docket = \n| OpinionAnnouncement = \n| Prior = Defendants convicted, Caroline County Circuit Court (January 6, 1959); [[motion to vacate]] judgment denied, Caroline County Circuit Court (January 22, 1959); affirmed in part, reversed and remanded, 147 [[South Eastern Reporter|S.E.2d]] 78 (Va. 1966); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, {{ussc|385|986|1966|el=no}}.\n| Subsequent = \n| Holding = Bans on interracial marriage violate the [[Equal Protection Clause]] and [[Due Process Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]].\n| OralArgument = https://www.oyez.org/cases/1960-1969/1966/1966_395/argument/\n| OralReargument =\n| Majority = Warren\n| JoinMajority =''unanimous''\n| Concurrence = Stewart\n| JoinConcurrence = \n| Concurrence2 = \n| JoinConcurrence2 = \n| Concurrence/Dissent = \n| JoinConcurrence/Dissent = \n| Dissent = \n| JoinDissent = \n| Dissent2 = \n| JoinDissent2 = \n| LawsApplied = [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. XIV]]; Va. Code \u00a7\u00a7 20\u201358, 20\u201359\n| Overturned previous case = ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]'' (1883)\n}}\n\n'''''Loving v. Virginia''''', 388 U.S. 1 (1967), was a [[Landmark decision|landmark]] decision of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] that struck down [[Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States|laws banning interracial marriage]] as violations of the [[Equal Protection Clause|Equal Protection]] and [[Due Process Clause]]s of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution]].<ref name=Loving>{{ussc|name=Loving v. Virginia|volume=388|page=1|pin=|year=1967}}</ref>{{sfnp|Nowak|Rotunda|2012|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;18.28(a), pp. 80\u201381}} The decision was followed by an increase in [[interracial marriages in the U.S.]] and is remembered annually on [[Loving Day]]. It has been the subject of several songs and three movies, including the 2016 film ''[[Loving (2016 film)|Loving]]''. Beginning in 2013, it was cited as precedent in U.S. federal court decisions holding restrictions on [[same-sex marriage in the United States]] unconstitutional, including in the 2015 Supreme Court decision ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]''.<ref name=Obergefell>{{ussc|name=Obergefell v. Hodges|volume=576|year=2015|docket=14-556}}</ref>\n\nThe case involved Mildred Loving, a [[person of color|woman of color]],{{notetag|Mildred Loving's precise racial background remains unclear. Most sources describe her as black, but she denied being black and often stated she was Native American. See the [[Loving v. Virginia#Plaintiffs|\"Plaintiffs\" section]] for details.}} and her white husband Richard Loving, who in 1958 were sentenced to a year in prison for marrying each other. Their marriage violated Virginia's [[Racial Integrity Act of 1924]], which criminalized marriage between people classified as \"[[White people|white]]\" and people classified as \"[[colored]]\". The Lovings appealed their conviction to the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]], which upheld it. They then appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court, which agreed to hear their case.\n\nOn June 12, 1967, the Court issued a unanimous decision in the Lovings' favor and overturned their convictions.  The Court struck down Virginia's anti-miscegenation law, ending all [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]]-based legal restrictions on [[marriage in the United States]]. Virginia had argued that its law was not a violation of the Equal Protection Clause because the punishment was the same regardless of the offender's race, and thus it \"equally burdened\" both whites and non-whites.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}} The Court found that the law nonetheless violated the Equal Protection Clause because it was based solely on \"distinctions drawn according to race\" and outlawed conduct\u2014namely, getting married\u2014that was otherwise generally accepted and which citizens were free to do.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}}\n\n==Background==\n===Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States===\n[[Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States]] had been in place in certain states since colonial days. In the [[Reconstruction Era]] in 1865, the [[Black Codes (United States)|Black Codes]] across the seven states of the lower South made intermarriage illegal.  The new [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] legislatures in six states repealed the restrictive laws. By 1894, when the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in the South had returned to power, the restriction had been reimposed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wallenstein |first1=Peter |title=Reconstruction, Segregation, and Miscegenation: Interracial Marriage and the Law in the Lower South, 1865\u20131900 |journal=American Nineteenth Century History |volume=6 |date=16 Aug 2006 |pages=57\u201376 |doi=10.1080/14664650500121827 |quote=On the eve of Congressional Reconstruction, all seven states of the Lower South had laws against interracial marriage. During the Republican interlude that began in 1867\u201368, six of the seven states (all but Georgia) suspended those laws, whether through judicial invalidation or legislative repeal. Yet by 1894 all six had restored such bans.}}</ref>\n\nA major concern was how to draw the line between black and white in a society in which white men had many children with enslaved black women. On the one hand, a person's reputation as black or white was usually decisive in practical matters. On the other hand, most laws used a \"one drop of blood\" rule, which meant that one black ancestor made a person black in the view of the law.<ref>Peter Wallenstein, \"Reconstruction, Segregation, and Miscegenation: Interracial Marriage and the Law in the Lower South, 1865\u20131900.\" ''American Nineteenth Century History'' 6#1 (2005): 57\u201376.</ref> In 1967, 16 states still retained anti-miscegenation laws, mainly in the [[Southern United States|American South]].<ref>''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 6.</ref>\n\n===Plaintiffs===\n[[Image:Mildred Jeter and Richard Loving.jpg|thumb|right|Mildred and Richard Loving in 1967]]\nMildred Delores Loving ([[n\u00e9e]] Jeter; July 22, 1939 \u2013 May 2, 2008) was the daughter of Musial (Byrd) Jeter and Theoliver Jeter.<ref>[http://www.memorialobituaries.com/memorials/memorials_print.cgi?memid=191270 Mildred Loving obituary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027192630/http://www.memorialobituaries.com/memorials/memorials_print.cgi?memid=191270 |date=2016-10-27 }} accessed 10/26/2016</ref> Mildred's racial identity has been a point of confusion. She has been noted as self-identifying as [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indian]]-[[Rappahannock people|Rappahannock]],<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4362508/loving-v-virginia-personas/|title=What You Didn't Know About Loving v. Virginia|website=Time|access-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215022952/http://time.com/4362508/loving-v-virginia-personas/|archivedate=2017-02-15}}</ref> but was also reported as being of [[Cherokee]], [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]], and [[African American]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlielawing.com/modhist_lovingv.virginia.pdf|title=''Loving v. Virginia'' and the Hegemony of \"Race\"|last=Lawing|first=Charles B.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704053526/http://www.charlielawing.com/modhist_lovingv.virginia.pdf|archivedate=July 4, 2007|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-06-10-loving_N.htm|title=Pioneer of interracial marriage looks back|last=Walker|first=Dionne|date=2007-06-10|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=2015-04-27}}</ref> During the trial, it seemed clear that she identified herself as black, especially as far as her own lawyer was concerned. However, upon her arrest, the police report identifies her as \"Indian\". She said in a 2004 interview, \"I have no black ancestry. I am Indian-Rappahannock.\" A possible contributing factor is that it was seen at the time of her arrest as advantageous to be \"anything but black\". There was an ingrained history in the state of the denial of African ancestry.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Additionally, the frequent racial mixing of [[Central Point, Virginia|Central Point]], where she lived, could have contributed to this fluid racial identity.<ref name=\"Staples\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/14/opinion/14wed4.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Loving v. Virginia and the Secret History of Race|last=Staples|first=Brent|date=2008-05-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Mildred was known as a quiet and humble woman.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rathbone|first=Mark|date=April 2009|title=Mildred Loving|url=|journal=General OneFile|volume=|pages=32+|via=}}</ref> She was born and raised in the same rural Virginia community as her husband, Richard.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lavender|first=Abraham|date=2014|title=Loving, Richard (1933\u20131975), and Mildred Loving (1939\u20132008)|url=|journal=Culture Wars in America: An Encyclopedia of Issues, Viewpoints, and Voices, Edited by Roger Chapman and James Ciment, 2nd Ed.|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nRichard Perry Loving (October 29, 1933 \u2013 June 29, 1975) was a white man, and the son of Lola (Allen) Loving and Twillie Loving. He was a construction worker. The 1830 census marks Lewis Loving, Richard's paternal ancestor, as having owned seven slaves. Richard's grandfather, T. P. Farmer, fought for the Confederacy in the Civil War.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4552130/loving-movie-racial-passing-history/|title=The White and Black Worlds of 'Loving v. Virginia'|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref> \u2018\u2019There\u2019s just a few people that live in this community,\u201d Richard said. \u201cA few white and a few colored.  And as I grew up, and as they grew up, we all helped one another.  It was all, as I say, mixed together to start with and just kept goin\u2019 that way.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|title=The Loving Couple|url= https://www.theattic.space/home-page-blogs/2019/11/7/the-loving-couple |website=The Attic|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nTheir families both lived in [[Caroline County, Virginia]]. The county adhered to strict [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow segregation laws]] but Central Point had been a visible mixed-race community since the 19th century.<ref name=\"Staples\"/> Richard's father worked for one of the wealthiest black men in the county for 25 years. Richard's closest companions were black, including those he drag-raced with and Mildred's older brothers. The couple met in high school and fell in love. Richard moved into the Jeter household when Mildred became pregnant.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nAfter the Supreme Court case, the couple moved back to Central Point, where Richard built them a house. The couple had three children: Donald, Peggy, and Sidney.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|title=Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage Dies at 68|author=Douglas Martin|date=May 6, 2008|accessdate=November 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701043346/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|archivedate=July 1, 2017|url-status=live|work=The New York Times|quote=The Lovings' son Donald died in 2000. In addition to her daughter, Peggy Fortune, who lives in Milford, Va., Mrs. Loving is survived by her son, Sidney, of Tappahannock, Va.; eight grandchildren; and 11 great-grandchildren.}}</ref> Richard Loving died aged 41 in 1975, when a drunk driver struck his car in [[Caroline County, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/07/01/archives/richard-p-loving-in-land-mark-suit-figure-in-high-court-ruling-on.html|title=Richard P. Loving; in Landmark Suit; Figure in High Court Ruling on Miscegenation Dies|date=July 1, 1975|work=The New York Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426211818/http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10D13FD3B58157493C3A9178CD85F418785F9|archivedate=April 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Mildred Loving lost her right eye in the same accident. She died of [[pneumonia]] on May 2, 2008, in her home in Central Point, aged 68.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2008|title=died: Mildred Jeter Loving (1939\u20132008)|url=|journal=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education|volume=60|page=83|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Criminal proceedings==\nAt the age of 18, Mildred became pregnant. In June 1958, the couple traveled to [[Washington, D.C.]] to marry, thereby evading Virginia's [[Racial Integrity Act of 1924]], which made marriage between whites and non-whites a crime.<ref>{{cite web|title = Racial Integrity Laws (1924\u20131930)|url = http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Racial_Integrity_Laws_of_the_1920s|website = www.encyclopediavirginia.org|accessdate = 2015-11-04|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151115151130/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/racial_integrity_laws_of_the_1920s|archivedate = 2015-11-15}}</ref> They returned to the small town of [[Central Point, Virginia]]. Based on an anonymous tip,<ref name=NYT>Martin, Douglas. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html \"Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage, Dies at 68\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201080047/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html |date=2016-12-01 }}, ''New York Times'', May 6, 2008.</ref> local police raided their home in the early morning hours of July 11, 1958,<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.biography.com/people/mildred-loving-5884| title =Mildred Loving - Civil Rights Activist - Biography.com| website =[[Biography.com]]| publisher =[[A&E Television Networks, LLC]]| access-date =2017-02-20| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20170211080301/http://www.biography.com/people/mildred-loving-5884| archivedate =2017-02-11}}</ref> hoping to find them having sex, given that interracial sex was then also illegal in Virginia. When the officers found the Lovings sleeping in their bed, Mildred pointed out their marriage certificate on the bedroom wall. They were told the certificate was not valid in Virginia.\n\nThe Lovings were charged under Section 20-58 of the Virginia Code, which prohibited interracial couples from being married out of state and then returning to Virginia, and Section 20\u201359, which classified [[miscegenation]] as a felony, punishable by a prison sentence of between one and five years.\n\nOn January 6, 1959, the Lovings pled guilty to \"cohabiting as man and wife, against the peace and dignity of the Commonwealth\". They were sentenced to one year in prison, with the sentence suspended on condition that the couple leave Virginia and not return together for at least 25 years. After their conviction, the couple moved to the [[District of Columbia]].<ref>''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 3 (\"On January 6, 1959, the Lovings pleaded guilty to the charge and were sentenced to one year in jail; however, the trial judge suspended the sentence for a period of 25 years on the condition that the Lovings leave the State and not return to Virginia together for 25 years&nbsp;... After their convictions, the Lovings took up residence in the District of Columbia.\")</ref>\n\n===Appellate proceedings===\nIn 1964, frustrated by their inability to travel together to visit their families in Virginia, as well as their social isolation and financial difficulties in Washington, Mildred Loving wrote in protest to [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Robert F. Kennedy]].<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/remember-jan-june08-loving_05-06 \"Mildred Loving, Key Figure in Civil Rights Era, Dies\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613230048/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/remember-jan-june08-loving_05-06/ |date=2017-06-13 }}, PBS Online News Hour, May 6, 2008</ref> Kennedy referred her to the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU).<ref name=NYT/> The ACLU assigned volunteer cooperating attorneys [[Bernard S. Cohen]] and [[Philip Hirschkop|Philip J. Hirschkop]], who filed a motion on behalf of the Lovings in the Virginia Caroline County Circuit Court, that requested the court to [[Vacated judgment|vacate]] the criminal judgments and set aside the Lovings' sentences on the grounds that the Virginia miscegenation statutes ran counter to the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]]'s [[Equal Protection Clause]].\n\nOn October 28, 1964, after waiting almost a year for a response to their motion, the ACLU attorneys brought a class action suit in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia. This prompted the county court judge in the case, Leon M. Bazile (1890\u20131967), to issue a ruling on the long-pending motion to vacate. Echoing [[Johann Friedrich Blumenbach]]'s 18th-century interpretation of race, Bazile wrote:\n\n{{quote|Almighty God created the races white, black, yellow, malay and red, and he placed them on separate continents. And but for the interference with his arrangement there would be no cause for such marriages. The fact that he separated the races shows that he did not intend for the races to mix.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opinion of Judge Bazile in Commonwealth v. Loving (January 22, 1965)|url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Opinion_of_Judge_Leon_M_Bazile_January_22_1965|website=www.encyclopediavirginia.org|accessdate=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128135102/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Opinion_of_Judge_Leon_M_Bazile_January_22_1965|archivedate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nOn January 22, 1965, a three-judge district court panel postponed decision on the federal class-action case while the Lovings appealed Judge Bazile's decision on constitutional grounds to the [[Supreme Court of Virginia|Virginia Supreme Court]]. Justice [[Harry L. Carrico]] (later Chief Justice of the Court) wrote an opinion for the court upholding the constitutionality of the anti-miscegenation statutes. While he upheld their criminal convictions, he directed that their sentence be modified.<ref>{{cite web|title = Loving v. Commonwealth (March 7, 1966)|url = http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Commonwealth_March_7_1966|website = www.encyclopediavirginia.org|accessdate = 2015-11-04|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910095234/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Commonwealth_March_7_1966|archivedate = September 10, 2015}}</ref> Carrico cited as authority the Virginia Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Naim v. Naim]]'' (1955) and argued that the Lovings' case was not a violation of the Equal Protection Clause because both the white and the non-white spouse were punished equally for the crime of miscegenation, an argument similar to that made by the United States Supreme Court in 1883 in ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]''.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Loving v. Commonwealth |vol=206 |reporter=Va. |opinion=924 |pinpoint= |court= |date=1966 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/virginia/supreme-court/1966/6163-1.html |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> However, the court did find the Lovings' sentences to be unconstitutionally vague, struck them down, and ordered them resentenced in the Caroline County Circuit Court.\n\nThe Lovings, still supported by the ACLU, appealed the decision to the United States Supreme Court, where Virginia was represented by [[Robert McIlwaine]] of the state's attorney general's office. The Lovings did not attend the oral arguments in Washington,<ref>Kate Sheppard, [https://www.motherjones.com/media/2012/02/the-loving-story-documentary-hbo {{\"'}}The Loving Story': How an Interracial Couple Changed a Nation\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220203224/https://www.motherjones.com/media/2012/02/the-loving-story-documentary-hbo |date=2017-02-20 }}, ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'', Feb 13, 2012.</ref> but one of their lawyers, [[Bernard S. Cohen]], conveyed the message he had been given by Richard Loving: \"Mr. Cohen, tell the Court I love my wife, and it is just unfair that I can't live with her in Virginia.\"<ref name=\"Oyez\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/1966/395|title=Loving v. Virginia oral argument transcript|accessdate=November 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115152456/https://www.oyez.org/cases/1966/395|archivedate=November 15, 2016}} Also quoted in [http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Virginia_1967 Loving v. Virginia (1967)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214144034/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Virginia_1967 |date=2012-12-14 }}, ''[[Encyclopedia Virginia]]''</ref>\n\n==Precedents==\n[[File:US miscegenation.svg|thumb|Date range U.S. states repealed anti-miscegenation laws: {{legend|#d3d3d3|No laws passed}}\n{{legend|#5b9e39|1780 to 1887}}\n{{legend|#f3ee66|1948 to 1967}}\n{{legend|#cc2f2f|After 1967}}]]\nBefore ''Loving v. Virginia'', there had been several cases on the subject of interracial sexual relations. Within the state of Virginia, on October 3, 1878, in ''Kinney v. The Commonwealth'', the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]] ruled that the marriage legalized in [[Washington, D.C.]] between Andrew Kinney, a black man, and Mahala Miller, a white woman, was \"invalid\" in Virginia.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=DeNeen|title=Before Loving v. Virginia, another interracial couple fought in court for their marriage|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/11/before-loving-v-virginia-another-interracial-couple-fought-in-court-for-their-marriage/|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=11 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611132258/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/11/before-loving-v-virginia-another-interracial-couple-fought-in-court-for-their-marriage/|archivedate=11 June 2017|df=mdy}}</ref> In the national case of ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]'' (1883), the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] ruled that the conviction of an Alabama couple for interracial sex, affirmed on appeal by the Alabama Supreme Court, did not violate the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]].<ref name=Pace>{{ussc|name=Pace v. Alabama|volume=106|page=583|year=1883}}</ref> Interracial marital sex was deemed a felony, whereas extramarital sex (\"adultery or fornication\") was only a misdemeanor. On appeal, the United States Supreme Court ruled that the criminalization of interracial sex was not a violation of the [[equal protection clause]] because whites and non-whites were punished in equal measure for the offense of engaging in interracial sex. The court did not need to affirm the constitutionality of the ban on interracial marriage that was also part of Alabama's anti-miscegenation law, since the plaintiff, Mr. Pace, had chosen not to appeal that section of the law. After ''Pace v. Alabama'', the constitutionality of anti-miscegenation laws banning marriage and sex between whites and non-whites remained unchallenged until the 1920s.\n\nIn ''Kirby v. Kirby'' (1921), Mr. Kirby asked the state of Arizona for an annulment of his marriage. He charged that his marriage was invalid because his wife was of \"negro\" descent, thus violating the state's anti-miscegenation law. The Arizona Supreme Court judged Mrs. Kirby's race by observing her physical characteristics and determined that she was of mixed race, therefore granting Mr. Kirby's annulment.<ref name=Pascoe_pp49-51>{{harvnb|Pascoe|1996|pp=49\u201351}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''Monks'' case (''[[Estate of Monks]]'', 4. Civ. 2835, Records of California Court of Appeals, Fourth district), the Superior Court of San Diego County in 1939 decided to invalidate the marriage of Marie Antoinette and Allan Monks because she was deemed to have \"one eighth negro blood\". The court case involved a legal challenge over the conflicting wills that had been left by the late Allan Monks; an old one in favor of a friend named Ida Lee, and a newer one in favor of his wife. Lee's lawyers charged that the marriage of the Monkses, which had taken place in Arizona, was invalid under Arizona state law because Marie Antoinette was \"a Negro\" and Alan had been white. Despite conflicting testimony by various expert witnesses, the judge defined Mrs. Monks' race by relying on the anatomical \"expertise\" of a surgeon. The judge ignored the arguments of an anthropologist and a biologist that it was impossible to tell a person's race from physical characteristics.<ref name=Pascoe_p56>{{harvnb|Pascoe |1996|p=56}}</ref>\n\nMonks then challenged the Arizona anti-miscegenation law itself, taking her case to the California Court of Appeals, Fourth District. Monks' lawyers pointed out that the anti-miscegenation law effectively prohibited Monks as a mixed-race person from marrying anyone: \"As such, she is prohibited from marrying a negro or any descendant of a negro, a Mongolian or an Indian, a Malay or a Hindu, or any descendants of any of them. Likewise&nbsp;... as a descendant of a negro she is prohibited from marrying a Caucasian or a descendant of a Caucasian.&nbsp;...\" The Arizona anti-miscegenation statute thus prohibited Monks from contracting a valid marriage in Arizona, and was therefore an unconstitutional constraint on her liberty. However, the court dismissed this argument as inapplicable, because the case presented involved not two mixed-race spouses but a mixed-race and a white spouse: \"Under the facts presented the appellant does not have the benefit of assailing the validity of the statute.\"<ref name=Pascoe_p60>{{harvnb|Pascoe |1996|p=60}}</ref> Dismissing Monks' appeal in 1942, the United States Supreme Court refused to reopen the issue.\n\nThe turning point came with ''[[Perez v. Sharp]]'' (1948), also known as ''Perez v. Lippold''. In ''Perez'', the [[Supreme Court of California]] recognized that bans on interracial marriage violated the Fourteenth Amendment of the Federal Constitution.\n\n==Supreme Court decision==\nOn June 12, 1967, the Supreme Court issued a unanimous 9\u20130 decision that overturned the Lovings' Virginia criminal convictions and struck down anti-miscegenation laws that forbade marriage between people of different races.\n\nThe Court's opinion was written by [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[Earl Warren]], and all the justices joined it.{{notetag|The decision also includes a very short concurring opinion\u2014only two sentences long\u2014written by Justice [[Potter Stewart]]. Stewart took the position that no state criminal law can be valid \"which makes the criminality  of an act depend upon the race of the actor,\" a standard which reflects Justice [[John Marshall Harlan]]'s dissent in 1896's ''[[Plessy v. Ferguson]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Schoff | first= Rebecca | year=2009 | title = Note: Deciding on Doctrine: Anti-Miscegnation Statutes and the Development of Equal Protection Analysis | url=http://www.virginialawreview.org/volumes/content/deciding-doctrine-anti-miscegenation-statutes-and-development-equal-protection | journal=Virginia Law Review | volume=95 | issue=3 | pages = 627\u201365}}.</ref>}} It began by rejecting Virginia's argument that the anti-miscegenation clause in its Racial Integrity Act did not violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment because the punishment for violating the statute was the same regardless of the offender's race\u2014that is, a white person who married a black person received the same punishment as black person who married a white person\u2014and therefore it \"equally burdened\" both whites and non-whites. The Court had upheld this \"equal burden\" argument 84 years earlier in the 1883 case ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]'', but in ''Loving'' it rejected it and overruled ''Pace'', stating: \"We reject the notion that the mere 'equal application' of a statute concerning racial classifications is enough to remove the classifications from the Fourteenth Amendment's proscription of all invidious racial discriminations.\"<ref>{{harvp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}}, quoting ''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 8.</ref> The Court ruled that because the races of the people involved were the only factors determining whether or not they broke the law, the law was therefore a violation of the Equal Protection Clause.{{sfnp|Nowak|Rotunda|2012|loc=\u00a7 18.28(a), pp. 80\u201381}}\n{{Quote\n|text=There can be no question but that Virginia's miscegenation statutes rest solely upon distinctions drawn according to race. The statutes proscribe generally accepted conduct if engaged in by members of different races. ... There can be no doubt that restricting the freedom to marry solely because of racial classifications violates the central meaning of the Equal Protection Clause.\n|source=''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 11\u201312.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}}\n}}\nAfter holding that Virginia's anti-miscegenation law violated the Equal Protection Clause, the Court concluded its opinion with a short section holding that it also violated the Fourteenth Amendment's [[Due Process Clause]], because it deprived its people of a constitutionally protected right without [[due process of law]].{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;10.2.1, p. 863}} It held that the freedom to marry is a fundamental right, and therefore that depriving Americans of this liberty on an arbitrary basis such as race was unconstitutional.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;10.2.1, p. 863}}\n{{Quote\n|text=The freedom to marry has long been recognized as one of the vital personal rights essential to the orderly pursuit of happiness by free men. Marriage is one of the \"basic civil rights of man,\" fundamental to our very existence and survival. To deny this fundamental freedom on so unsupportable a basis as the racial classifications embodied in these statutes, classifications so directly subversive of the principle of equality at the heart of the Fourteenth Amendment, is surely to deprive all the State's citizens of liberty without due process of law.\n|source=''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 12 (case citations omitted).{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;10.2.1, p. 863}}\n}}\n\n==Effects==\n\n===For interracial marriage===\nDespite the Supreme Court's decision, anti-miscegenation laws remained on the books in several states, although the decision had made them unenforceable. Local judges in [[Alabama]] continued to enforce that state's anti-miscegenation statute until the Nixon administration obtained a ruling from a U.S. District Court in ''United States v. Brittain'' in 1970.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=United States v. Brittain |vol=319 |reporter=F. Supp. |opinion=1058 |pinpoint= |court=[[N.D. Ala.]] |date=1970 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/319/1058/2134867/ |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenthal|first1=Jack|title=Government Seeks to Allow A Mixed Marriage in Alabama|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/12/04/355155472.pdf|accessdate=January 25, 2015|work=New York Times|date=December 4, 1970}}</ref> In 2000, Alabama became the last state to adapt its laws to the Supreme Court's decision, when 60% of voters endorsed a [[ballot initiative]] that removed anti-miscegenation language from the state constitution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/weekinreview/november-5-11-marry-at-will.html |title=November 5\u201311; Marry at Will |work=New York Times |date=November 12, 2000 |accessdate=May 27, 2009 |quote=The margin by which the measure passed was itself a statement. A clear majority, 60 percent, voted to remove the miscegenation statute from the state constitution, but 40 percent of Alabamans \u2013 nearly 526,000 people \u2013 voted to keep it. |first=Somini |last=Sengupta |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821110359/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/weekinreview/november-5-11-marry-at-will.html |archivedate=August 21, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Loving v. Virginia'', the number of interracial marriages continued to increase across the United States<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/18090277 |title=Interracial marriage flourishes in U.S. |publisher=NBC News |date=April 15, 2007 |accessdate=December 13, 2012 }}</ref> and in the South. In Georgia, for instance, the number of interracial marriages increased from 21 in 1967 to 115 in 1970.<ref>Aldridge, ''The Changing Nature of Interracial Marriage in Georgia: A Research Note'', 1973</ref> At the national level, 0.4% of marriages were interracial in 1960, 2.0% in 1980,<ref name=\"UnitedStatesCensusData\">{{cite web| url =https://www.census.gov/population/socdemo/race/interractab1.txt| title =Table 1. Race of Wife by Race of Husband: 1960, 1970, 1980, 1991, and 1992| date =1994-07-05| website =[[census.gov]]| publisher =[[U.S. Bureau of the Census]]| access-date =2017-02-20| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20170304155503/https://www.census.gov/population/socdemo/race/interractab1.txt| archivedate =2017-03-04}}</ref> 12% in 2013,<ref>{{cite web|title=Interracial marriage: Who is 'marrying out'?|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/06/12/interracial-marriage-who-is-marrying-out/|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|accessdate=11 August 2016|date=12 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812004242/http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/06/12/interracial-marriage-who-is-marrying-out/|archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> and 16% in 2015, almost 50 years after ''Loving''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Intermarriage across the U.S. by metro area|url=http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/interactives/intermarriage-across-the-u-s-by-metro-area/|website=Pew Research Center's Social & Demographic Trends Project|accessdate=11 June 2017|date=18 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606132122/http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/interactives/intermarriage-across-the-u-s-by-metro-area/|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===For same-sex marriage===\n''Loving v. Virginia'' was discussed in the context of the public debate about [[same-sex marriage in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Trei |first=Lisa |url=http://news.stanford.edu/pr/2007/pr-rosenfeld-061307.html |title=''Loving v. Virginia'' provides roadmap for same-sex marriage advocates |publisher=News.stanford.edu |date=June 13, 2007 |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213011039/http://news.stanford.edu/pr/2007/pr-rosenfeld-061307.html |archivedate=December 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Hern\u00e1ndez v. Robles|Hernandez v. Robles]]'' (2006), the majority opinion of the [[New York Court of Appeals]]\u2014that state's highest court\u2014declined to rely on the ''Loving'' case when deciding whether a right to same-sex marriage existed, holding that \"the historical background of ''Loving'' is different from the history underlying this case.\"<ref name=\"hernandezvrobles\">{{cite court |litigants=Hernandez v. Robles |vol=855 |reporter=N.E.3d |opinion=1 |pinpoint= |court=N.Y. |date=2006 |url=http://www.courts.state.ny.us/reporter/3dseries/2006/2006_05239.htm |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> In the 2010 federal district court decision in ''[[Perry v. Schwarzenegger]]'', overturning [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|California's Proposition 8]] which restricted marriage to opposite-sex couples, Judge [[Vaughn R. Walker]] cited ''Loving v. Virginia'' to conclude that \"the [constitutional] right to marry protects an individual's choice of marital partner regardless of gender\".<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Perry v. Schwarzenegger |vol=704 |reporter=F. Supp. 2d |opinion=921 |pinpoint= |court=[[N.D. Cal.]] |date=2010 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20101015624 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> On narrower grounds, the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/08/us/marriage-ban-violates-constitution-court-rules.html |first1=Adam |last1=Nagoruney |date=February 7, 2012 |title=Court Strikes Down Ban on Gay Marriage in California |work=New York Times |accessdate=February 8, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211122706/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/08/us/marriage-ban-violates-constitution-court-rules.html |archivedate=February 11, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"9th\">{{cite court |litigants=Perry v. Brown |vol=671 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1052 |pinpoint= |court=[[9th Cir.]] |date=2012 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120207000t |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, on the 40th anniversary of the Supreme Court's decision in ''Loving'', Mildred Loving issued the following statement:\n{{quote|My generation was bitterly divided over something that should have been so clear and right. The majority believed that what the judge said, that it was God's plan to keep people apart, and that government should discriminate against people in love. But I have lived long enough now to see big changes. The older generation's fears and prejudices have given way, and today's young people realize that if someone loves someone they have a right to marry.\n\nSurrounded as I am now by wonderful children and grandchildren, not a day goes by that I don't think of Richard and our love, our right to marry, and how much it meant to me to have that freedom to marry the person precious to me, even if others thought he was the \"wrong kind of person\" for me to marry. I believe all Americans, no matter their race, no matter their sex, no matter their sexual orientation, should have that same freedom to marry. Government has no business imposing some people's religious beliefs over others. Especially if it denies people's civil rights.\n\nI am still not a political person, but I am proud that Richard's and my name is on a court case that can help reinforce the love, the commitment, the fairness, and the family that so many people, black or white, young or old, gay or straight seek in life. I support the freedom to marry for all. That's what Loving, and loving, are all about.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/acsblog/mildred-loving-endorses-marriage-equality-for-same-sex-couples/|title=Mildred Loving Endorses Marriage Equality for Same-Sex Couples|publisher=[[American Constitution Society]]|date=June 15, 2007|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/daily-dish/archive/2007/06/mildred-loving-40-years-later/227582/|title=Mildred Loving, 40 Years Later|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=June 18, 2007|accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|title=Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage, Dies at 68|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=May 6, 2008|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nUp until 2014, five [[United States court of appeals|U.S. Courts of Appeals]] considered the constitutionality of state bans on same-sex marriage. In doing so they interpreted or used the ''Loving'' ruling differently:\n\n*The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth]] and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit|Tenth]] Circuits used ''Loving'' along with other cases like ''[[Zablocki v. Redhail]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Zablocki v. Redhail|volume=434|page=374|pin=|year=1978}}</ref> and ''[[Turner v. Safley]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Turner v. Safley|volume=482|page=78|pin=|year=1987}}</ref> to demonstrate that the U.S. Supreme Court has recognized a \"fundamental right to marry\" that a state cannot restrict unless it meets the court's \"[[heightened scrutiny]]\" standard. Using that standard, both courts struck down state bans on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Bostic v. Shaefer |vol=760 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=352 |pinpoint=376 |court=[[4th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20140728145 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=Perhaps most notably, in ''Loving v. Virginia'', the Supreme Court invalidated a Virginia law that prohibited white individuals from marrying individuals of other races. The Court explained that '[t]he freedom to marry has long been recognized as one of the vital personal rights essential to the orderly pursuit of happiness by free men' and that no valid basis justified the Virginia law's infringement of that right. [citations omitted]}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants=Kitchen v. Herbert |vol=755 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1193 |pinpoint= |court=[[10th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20140625074 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref>\n*Two other courts of appeals, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|Seventh]] and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth]] Circuits, struck down state bans on the basis of a different line of argument. Instead of \"fundamental rights\" analysis, they reviewed bans on same-sex marriage as discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation. The former cited ''Loving'' to demonstrate that the Supreme Court did not accept tradition as a justification for limiting access to marriage.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Baskin v. Bogan |vol=766 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=648 |pinpoint= |court=[[7th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20140904126 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> The latter cited ''Loving'' as quoted in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'' on the question of federalism: \"state laws defining or regulating marriage, of course, must respect the constitutional rights of persons\".<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Latta v. Otter |vol=771 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=456 |pinpoint=474 |court= |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20141007102 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref>\n*The only Court of Appeals to uphold state bans on same-sex marriage, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|Sixth Circuit]], said that when the ''Loving'' decision discussed marriage it was referring only to marriage between persons of the opposite sex.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=DeBoer v. Snyder |vol=772 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=388 |pinpoint=411 |court=[[6th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20141106144 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=Matters do not change because ''Loving v. Virginia'' held that 'marriage' amounts to a fundamental right.&nbsp;... In referring to 'marriage' rather than \"opposite-sex marriage\", ''Loving'' confirmed only that 'opposite-sex marriage' would have been considered redundant, not that marriage included same-sex couples. ''Loving'' did not change the definition. [citations omitted]}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' (2015), the Supreme Court invoked ''Loving'', among other cases, as precedent for its holding that states are required to allow same-sex marriages under both the Equal Protection Clause and the Due Process Clause of the Constitution.<ref name=Obergefell/> The court's decision in ''Obergefell'' cited ''Loving'' nearly a dozen times, and was based on the same principles \u2013 equality and an [[unenumerated right]] to marriage. During oral argument, the eventual author of the majority opinion, Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]], noted that the ruling holding racial segregation unconstitutional and the ruling holding bans on interracial marriage unconstitutional (''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]'' in 1954 and ''Loving v. Virginia'' in 1967, respectively) were made about 13 years apart, much like the ruling holding bans on same-sex sexual activity unconstitutional and the eventual ruling holding bans on same-sex marriage unconstitutional (''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'' in 2003 and ''Obergefell v. Hodges'' in 2015, respectively).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Amar|first1=Akhil Reed|title=Anthony Kennedy and the Ghost of Earl Warren|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2015/07/06/obergefell_v_hodges_anthony_kennedy_continues_the_legacy_of_earl_warren.html|accessdate=6 July 2015|work=Slate|date=6 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707032841/http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2015/07/06/obergefell_v_hodges_anthony_kennedy_continues_the_legacy_of_earl_warren.html|archivedate=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Remembrance and representation in popular culture==\n[[File:Graves of Mildred and Richard Loving.jpg|thumb|Graves of the Lovings in the St. Stephen's Baptist Church cemetery, Central Point]]\nIn the United States, June 12, the date of the decision, has become known as [[Loving Day]], an annual unofficial celebration of interracial marriages. In 2014, Mildred Loving was honored as one of the [[Library of Virginia]]'s \"[[Virginia Women in History]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lva.virginia.gov/public/vawomen/2014/honoree.htm?bio=Loving|title=Virginia Women in History: Mildred Delores Jeter Loving|publisher=Library of Virginia|accessdate=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321185328/http://www.lva.virginia.gov/public/vawomen/2014/honoree.htm?bio=Loving|archivedate=21 March 2015}}</ref> In 2017, the [[Virginia Department of Historic Resources]] dedicated a state [[historical marker]], which tells the story of the Lovings, outside the [[Patrick Henry Building]] in Richmond \u2013  the former site of the [[Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia to honor interracial marriage with state historical marker|url=http://wtvr.com/2017/06/08/interracial-marriage-historical-marker/|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=WTVR.com|date=8 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608185356/http://wtvr.com/2017/06/08/interracial-marriage-historical-marker/|archivedate=8 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe story of the Lovings became the basis of several films:\n* The first, ''[[Mr. and Mrs. Loving]]'' (1996), was written and directed by [[Richard Friedenberg]] and starred [[Lela Rochon]], [[Timothy Hutton]], and [[Ruby Dee]].<ref>*{{IMDb title|id=0117098|title=Mr. & Mrs. Loving}}</ref> According to Mildred Loving, \"not much of it was very true. The only part of it right was I had three children.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Dionne Walker|publisher=USAToday.com|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-06-10-loving_N.htm|title=Pioneer of interracial marriage looks back|date=June 10, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509035254/http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-06-10-loving_N.htm|archivedate=May 9, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"iht\">{{cite news | title=40 years of interracial marriage: Mildred Loving reflects on breaking the color barrier | agency=Associated Press | work=[[International Herald-Tribune]] | date=June 9, 2007 | accessdate=April 28, 2008 | url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/10/america/NA-FEA-GEN-US-Loving-Anniversary.php | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508202344/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/10/america/NA-FEA-GEN-US-Loving-Anniversary.php | archivedate=May 8, 2008 }}</ref> \n* The second film, Nancy Buirski's documentary ''The Loving Story,'' premiered on [[HBO]] in February 2012<ref name=\"lovings-hbo\">{{cite news|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/arts/television/the-loving-story-an-hbo-documentary.html|title=Scenes From a Marriage That Segregationists Tried to Break Up|first=Alessandra|last=Stanley|date=February 13, 2012|work=New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214075848/http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/arts/television/the-loving-story-an-hbo-documentary.html|archivedate=February 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://icarusfilms.com/new2012/ls.html The Loving Story] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612142413/http://icarusfilms.com/new2012/ls.html |date=2012-06-12 }}, accessed March 25, 2015</ref> and won a [[Peabody Award]] that year.<ref>[http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/the-loving-story 72nd Annual Peabody Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911220051/http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/the-loving-story |date=2014-09-11 }}, May 2013.</ref>\n* A third film, ''[[Loving (2016 film)|Loving]]'', was released in 2016, directed by [[Jeff Nichols]] and starring [[Ruth Negga]] and [[Joel Edgerton]] as the Lovings. The film is based on Buirski's documentary. Negga received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for her performance.\n* A four-part film, ''The Loving Generation'', premiered on [[First Look Media|Topic.com]] in February 2018. Directed and produced by [[Lacey Schwartz]] and Mehret Mandefro, it explores the lives of biracial children born after the ''Loving'' decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.topic.com/the-loving-generation |title=The Loving Generation |publisher=[[First Look Media|Topic.com]] |accessdate=February 18, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217162449/https://www.topic.com/the-loving-generation |archivedate=February 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theroot.com/the-loving-generation-explores-the-lives-of-biracial-ch-1822767412|title=The Loving Generation Explores the Lives of Biracial Children Born After Mixed-Race Marriages Were Legalized|last=Branigin|first=Anne|date=February 10, 2018|work=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|access-date=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216030806/https://www.theroot.com/the-loving-generation-explores-the-lives-of-biracial-ch-1822767412|archivedate=February 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/10/opinion/sunday/black-with-some-white-privilege.html|title=Black With (Some) White Privilege|last=Holmes|first=Anna|authorlink=Anna Holmes|date=February 10, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214184644/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/10/opinion/sunday/black-with-some-white-privilege.html|archivedate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn music, [[Nanci Griffith]]'s 2009 album ''[[The Loving Kind (Nanci Griffith album)|The Loving Kind]]'' is named for the Lovings and includes a song about them. [[Roy Zimmerman (satirist)|Satirist Roy Zimmerman]]'s 2009 song ''The Summer of Loving''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xQWrasoNS24 |title=\"Summer of Loving\" - Roy Zimmerman |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-06-11 |accessdate=2019-04-05}}</ref> is about the Lovings and their 1967 case, making reference to the hippies' \"[[Summer of Love]]\" of that same year.\n\nA 2015 novel by the French journalist Gilles Biassette, ''L'amour des Loving'' (\"The Love of the Lovings\", {{ISBN|978-2917559598}}), recounts the life of the Lovings and their case.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mahuzier|first1=Marc|title=L'amour en noir et blanc|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/lamour-en-noir-et-blanc-3498156|accessdate=22 June 2015|work=[[Ouest-France]]|date=21 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924160041/http://www.ouest-france.fr/lamour-en-noir-et-blanc-3498156|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref> A [[photo-essay]] about the couple by Grey Villet, created just before the case, was republished in 2017.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Villet|first1=Barbara|last2=Villet|first2=Grey|title=The Lovings: An Intimate Portrait|date=February 14, 2017|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=978-1616895563}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{notefoot}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* {{cite book | first=Erwin | last=Chemerinsky | title=Constitutional Law: Principles and Policies | edition= 6th | location=New York | publisher=Wolters Kluwer | year=2019 | isbn=978-1-4548-9574-9 | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book | first1=John E. | last1=Nowak | first2=Ronald D. | last2=Rotunda | title=Treatise on Constitutional Law: Substance and Procedure | year=2012 | location=Eagan, Minnesota | publisher=West Thomson/Reuters| edition= 5th | oclc = 798148265 | ref=harv}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Aldridge |first=Delores |title=The Changing Nature of Interracial Marriage in Georgia: A Research Note |journal=Journal of Marriage and the Family |volume=35 |issue=4 |year=1973 |pages=641\u2013642 |doi=10.2307/350877 |jstor=350877 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Annella |first=M. |title=Interracial Marriages in Washington, D.C |journal=Journal of Negro Education |volume=36 |issue=4 |year=1967 |pages=428\u2013433 |doi=10.2307/2294264 |jstor=2294264 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Barnett |first=Larry |title=Research on International and Interracial Marriages |journal=Marriage and Family Living |volume=25 |issue=1 |year=1963 |pages=105\u2013107 |doi=10.2307/349019 |jstor=349019 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Brower |first=Brock |title='Irrepressible Intimacies'. Review of ''Interracial Intimacies: Sex, Marriage, Identity, and Adoption'', by Randall L. Kennedy |journal=Journal of Blacks in Higher Education |volume=40 |issue=40 |year=2003 |pages=120\u2013124 |doi=10.2307/3134064 |jstor=3134064 |last2=Kennedy |first2=Randall L.}}\n*Christopher Leslie (2004) ''[http://lawdigitalcommons.bc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3406&context=bclr Justice Alito's Dissent in Loving v. Virginia]'', University of California, p.&nbsp;1564.\n*{{Cite journal |last=Coolidge |first=David Orgon |title=Playing the Loving Card: Same-Sex Marriage and the Politics of Analogy |journal=BYU Journal of Public Law |volume=12 |year=1998 |issue= |pages=201\u2013238 |url=http://digitalcommons.law.byu.edu/jpl/vol12/iss2/2 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=DeCoste |first=F. C. |title=The ''Halpren'' Transformation: Same-Sex Marriage, Civil Society, and the Limits of Liberal Law |journal=Alberta Law Review |volume=41 |year=2003 |issue= 2|pages=619\u2013642 |doi=10.29173/alr1338 |doi-access=free }}\n*Dorothy Robert (2014) ''[http://www.nylslawreview.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/16/2015/02/Volume-59-1.Roberts.pdf Loving v. Virginia as a civil rights decision]'', p.&nbsp;177.\n*{{Cite journal |last=Foeman |first=Anita Kathy |lastauthoramp=yes |first2=Teresa |last2=Nance |title=From Miscegenation to Multiculturalism: Perceptions and Stages of Interracial Relationship Development |journal=Journal of Black Studies |volume=29 |issue=4 |year=1999 |pages=540\u2013557 |doi=10.1177/002193479902900405}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Hopkins |first=C. Quince |title=Variety in U.S Kinship Practices, Substantive Due Process Analysis and the Right to Marry |journal=BYU Journal of Public Law |volume=18 |year=2004 |issue= |pages=665\u2013679 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Kalmijn |first=Matthijs |title=Intermarriage and Homogamy: Causes, Patterns, Trends |journal=Annual Review of Sociology |volume=24 |issue= 24|year=1998 |pages=395\u2013421 |doi=10.1146/annurev.soc.24.1.395|pmid=12321971 |hdl=1874/13605 |hdl-access=free }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Koppelman |first=Andrew |title=The Miscegenation Analogy: Sodomy Law as Sex Discrimination |journal=[[Yale Law Journal]] |volume=98 |issue= 1|year=1988 |pages=145\u2013164 |doi=10.2307/796648 |jstor=796648 |url=https://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/ylj/vol98/iss1/3 }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Newbeck |first=Phyl |title=Virginia hasn't always been for lovers |date= 2004 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Pascoe |first=Peggy |title=Miscegenation Law, Court Cases, and Ideologies of 'Race' in Twentieth-Century America |journal=Journal of American History |volume=83 |issue=1 |year=1996 |pages=44\u201369 |ref=harv |doi=10.2307/2945474|jstor=2945474 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Pratt |first1=Robert A. |title=Crossing the color line: A historical assessment and personal narrative of Loving v. Virginia |journal=Howard Law Journal |volume=41 |year=1997 |page=229 }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Villet |first=Grey |title=The Lovings: An Intimate Portrait |date= 2017}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Wadlington |first=Walter |title=Domestic Relations |date=November 1967 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wallenstein |first1=Peter |title=Race, Sex, and the Freedom to Marry: Loving v. Virginia |year=2014 |isbn=978-0-7006-2000-5 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Wildman |first=Stephanie |title=Interracial Intimacy and the Potential for Social Change: Review of ''Interracial Intimacy: The Regulation of Race and Romance'' by Rachel F. Moran |journal=Berkeley Women's Law Journal |volume=17 |year=2002 |pages=153\u2013164 |doi=10.2139/ssrn.309743 |url=http://digitalcommons.law.scu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1633&context=facpubs }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Yancey |first=George |lastauthoramp=yes |first2=Sherelyn |last2=Yancey |title=Interracial Dating: Evidence from Personal Advertisements |journal=Journal of Family Issues |volume=19 |issue=3 |year=1998 |pages=334\u2013348 |doi=10.1177/019251398019003006 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n\n=== Links with the text of the court's decision ===\n*{{wikisource-inline|Loving v. Virginia|''Loving v. Virginia''}}\n*{{caselaw source\n | case=''Loving v. Virginia'', {{ussc|388|1|1967|el=no}}\n | cornell =https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/388/1\n | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/107480/loving-v-virginia/\n | findlaw=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/388/1.html\n | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=5103666188878568597\n | justia=https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/388/1/case.html\n | loc =http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep388/usrep388001/usrep388001.pdf\n | openjurist =https://openjurist.org/388/us/1\n | oyez =https://www.oyez.org/cases/1966/395\n}}\n{{reflist|group=X}}\n\n=== Other external links ===\n*[http://www.abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=3277875&page=1n A Groundbreaking Interracial Marriage; ''Loving v. Virginia'' at 40.] ''[[ABC News]]'' interview with Mildred Jeter Loving & video of original 1967 broadcast. June 14, 2007.\n*[https://www.oyez.org/oyez/resource/case/214/ Resources] at [[Oyez.org]] including complete audio of the oral arguments.\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=10889047 ''Loving'' Decision: 40 Years of Legal Interracial Unions], [[National Public Radio]]: ''[[All Things Considered]]'', June 11, 2007.\n*[http://writ.news.findlaw.com/grossman/20070612.html The Fortieth Anniversary of ''Loving v. Virginia'': The Legal Legacy of the Case that Ended Legal Prohibitions on Interracial Marriage], [[Findlaw]] commentary by Joanna Grossman.\n*Chin, Gabriel and Hrishi Karthikeyan, (2002) ''Asian Law Journal'', vol. 9 [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=283998 \"Preserving Racial Identity: Population Patterns and the Application of Anti-Miscegenation Statutes to Asian Americans, 1910\u20131950\"]\n\n{{Civil rights movement|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{US14thAmendment}}\n\n{{Virginia Women in History}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loving V. Virginia}}\n[[Category:1967 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:1967 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:20th century American trials]]\n[[Category:Civil rights movement case law]]\n[[Category:African-American history of Virginia]]\n[[Category:American Civil Liberties Union litigation]]\n[[Category:Caroline County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Legal history of Virginia]]\n[[Category:Marriage, unions and partnerships in the United States]]\n[[Category:Multiracial affairs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Native American history]]\n[[Category:Race and law in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States equal protection case law]]\n[[Category:United States family case law]]\n[[Category:United States substantive due process case law]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Warren Court]]\n[[Category:Rappahannock people]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court decisions that overrule a prior Supreme Court decision]]\n[[Category:Intercultural and interracial relationships]]\n[[Category:June 1967 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|U.S. Supreme Court case abolishing restrictions on interracial marriage}}\n{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n| Litigants = Loving v. Virginia\n| ArgueDate = April 10\n| ArgueYear = 1967\n| DecideDate = June 12\n| DecideYear = 1967\n| FullName = Richard Perry Loving, Mildred Jeter Loving v. Virginia\n| USVol = 388\n| USPage = 1\n| ParallelCitations = 87 S. Ct. 1817; 18 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 1010; 1967 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1082\n| Docket = \n| OpinionAnnouncement = \n| Prior = Defendants convicted, Caroline County Circuit Court (January 6, 1959); [[motion to vacate]] judgment denied, Caroline County Circuit Court (January 22, 1959); affirmed in part, reversed and remanded, 147 [[South Eastern Reporter|S.E.2d]] 78 (Va. 1966); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, {{ussc|385|986|1966|el=no}}.\n| Subsequent = \n| Holding = Bans on interracial marriage violate the [[Equal Protection Clause]] and [[Due Process Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]].\n| OralArgument = https://www.oyez.org/cases/1960-1969/1966/1966_395/argument/\n| OralReargument =\n| Majority = Warren\n| JoinMajority =''unanimous''\n| Concurrence = Stewart\n| JoinConcurrence = \n| Concurrence2 = \n| JoinConcurrence2 = \n| Concurrence/Dissent = \n| JoinConcurrence/Dissent = \n| Dissent = \n| JoinDissent = \n| Dissent2 = \n| JoinDissent2 = \n| LawsApplied = [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. XIV]]; Va. Code \u00a7\u00a7 20\u201358, 20\u201359\n| Overturned previous case = ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]'' (1883)\n}}\n\n'''''Loving v. Virginia''''', 388 U.S. 1 (1967), was a [[Landmark decision|landmark]] decision of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] that struck down [[Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States|laws banning interracial marriage]] as violations of the [[Equal Protection Clause|Equal Protection]] and [[Due Process Clause]]s of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution]].<ref name=Loving>{{ussc|name=Loving v. Virginia|volume=388|page=1|pin=|year=1967}}</ref>{{sfnp|Nowak|Rotunda|2012|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;18.28(a), pp. 80\u201381}} The decision was followed by an increase in [[interracial marriages in the U.S.]] and is remembered annually on [[Loving Day]]. It has been the subject of several songs and three movies, including the 2016 film ''[[Loving (2016 film)|Loving]]''. Beginning in 2013, it was cited as precedent in U.S. federal court decisions holding restrictions on [[same-sex marriage in the United States]] unconstitutional, including in the 2015 Supreme Court decision ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]''.<ref name=Obergefell>{{ussc|name=Obergefell v. Hodges|volume=576|year=2015|docket=14-556}}</ref>\n\nThe case involved Mildred Loving, a [[person of color|woman of color]],{{notetag|Mildred Loving's precise racial background remains unclear. Most sources describe her as black, but she denied being black and often stated she was Native American. See the [[Loving v. Virginia#Plaintiffs|\"Plaintiffs\" section]] for details.}} and her white husband Richard Loving, who in 1958 were sentenced to a year in prison for marrying each other. Their marriage violated Virginia's [[Racial Integrity Act of 1924]], which criminalized marriage between people classified as \"[[White people|white]]\" and people classified as \"[[colored]]\". The Lovings appealed their conviction to the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]], which upheld it. They then appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court, which agreed to hear their case.\n\nOn June 12, 1967, the Court issued a unanimous decision in the Lovings' favor and overturned their convictions.  The Court struck down Virginia's anti-miscegenation law, ending all [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]]-based legal restrictions on [[marriage in the United States]]. Virginia had argued that its law was not a violation of the Equal Protection Clause because the punishment was the same regardless of the offender's race, and thus it \"equally burdened\" both whites and non-whites.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}} The Court found that the law nonetheless violated the Equal Protection Clause because it was based solely on \"distinctions drawn according to race\" and outlawed conduct\u2014namely, getting married\u2014that was otherwise generally accepted and which citizens were free to do.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}}\n\n==Background==\n===Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States===\n[[Anti-miscegenation laws in the United States]] had been in place in certain states since colonial days. In the [[Reconstruction Era]] in 1865, the [[Black Codes (United States)|Black Codes]] across the seven states of the lower South made intermarriage illegal.  The new [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] legislatures in six states repealed the restrictive laws. By 1894, when the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in the South had returned to power, the restriction had been reimposed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wallenstein |first1=Peter |title=Reconstruction, Segregation, and Miscegenation: Interracial Marriage and the Law in the Lower South, 1865\u20131900 |journal=American Nineteenth Century History |volume=6 |date=16 Aug 2006 |pages=57\u201376 |doi=10.1080/14664650500121827 |quote=On the eve of Congressional Reconstruction, all seven states of the Lower South had laws against interracial marriage. During the Republican interlude that began in 1867\u201368, six of the seven states (all but Georgia) suspended those laws, whether through judicial invalidation or legislative repeal. Yet by 1894 all six had restored such bans.}}</ref>\n\nA major concern was how to draw the line between black and white in a society in which white men had many children with enslaved black women. On the one hand, a person's reputation as black or white was usually decisive in practical matters. On the other hand, most laws used a \"one drop of blood\" rule, which meant that one black ancestor made a person black in the view of the law.<ref>Peter Wallenstein, \"Reconstruction, Segregation, and Miscegenation: Interracial Marriage and the Law in the Lower South, 1865\u20131900.\" ''American Nineteenth Century History'' 6#1 (2005): 57\u201376.</ref> In 1967, 16 states still retained anti-miscegenation laws, mainly in the [[Southern United States|American South]].<ref>''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 6.</ref>\n\n===Plaintiffs===\n[[Image:Mildred Jeter and Richard Loving.jpg|thumb|right|Mildred and Richard Loving in 1967]]\nMildred Delores Loving ([[n\u00e9e]] Jeter; July 22, 1939 \u2013 May 2, 2008) was the daughter of Musial (Byrd) Jeter and Theoliver Jeter.<ref>[http://www.memorialobituaries.com/memorials/memorials_print.cgi?memid=191270 Mildred Loving obituary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027192630/http://www.memorialobituaries.com/memorials/memorials_print.cgi?memid=191270 |date=2016-10-27 }} accessed 10/26/2016</ref> Mildred's racial identity has been a point of confusion. She has been noted as self-identifying as [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indian]]-[[Rappahannock people|Rappahannock]],<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4362508/loving-v-virginia-personas/|title=What You Didn't Know About Loving v. Virginia|website=Time|access-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215022952/http://time.com/4362508/loving-v-virginia-personas/|archivedate=2017-02-15}}</ref> but was also reported as being of [[Cherokee]], [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]], and [[African American]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlielawing.com/modhist_lovingv.virginia.pdf|title=''Loving v. Virginia'' and the Hegemony of \"Race\"|last=Lawing|first=Charles B.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704053526/http://www.charlielawing.com/modhist_lovingv.virginia.pdf|archivedate=July 4, 2007|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-06-10-loving_N.htm|title=Pioneer of interracial marriage looks back|last=Walker|first=Dionne|date=2007-06-10|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=2015-04-27}}</ref> During the trial, it seemed clear that she identified herself as black, especially as far as her own lawyer was concerned. However, upon her arrest, the police report identifies her as \"Indian\". She said in a 2004 interview, \"I have no black ancestry. I am Indian-Rappahannock.\" A possible contributing factor is that it was seen at the time of her arrest as advantageous to be \"anything but black\". There was an ingrained history in the state of the denial of African ancestry.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Additionally, the frequent racial mixing of [[Central Point, Virginia|Central Point]], where she lived, could have contributed to this fluid racial identity.<ref name=\"Staples\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/14/opinion/14wed4.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Loving v. Virginia and the Secret History of Race|last=Staples|first=Brent|date=2008-05-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Mildred was known as a quiet and humble woman.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rathbone|first=Mark|date=April 2009|title=Mildred Loving|url=|journal=General OneFile|volume=|pages=32+|via=}}</ref> She was born and raised in the same rural Virginia community as her husband, Richard.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lavender|first=Abraham|date=2014|title=Loving, Richard (1933\u20131975), and Mildred Loving (1939\u20132008)|url=|journal=Culture Wars in America: An Encyclopedia of Issues, Viewpoints, and Voices, Edited by Roger Chapman and James Ciment, 2nd Ed.|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nRichard Perry Loving (October 29, 1933 \u2013 June 29, 1975) was a white man, and the son of Lola (Allen) Loving and Twillie Loving. He was a construction worker. The 1830 census marks Lewis Loving, Richard's paternal ancestor, as having owned seven slaves. Richard's grandfather, T. P. Farmer, fought for the Confederacy in the Civil War.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4552130/loving-movie-racial-passing-history/|title=The White and Black Worlds of 'Loving v. Virginia'|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref> \u2018\u2019There\u2019s just a few people that live in this community,\u201d Richard said. \u201cA few white and a few colored.  And as I grew up, and as they grew up, we all helped one another.  It was all, as I say, mixed together to start with and just kept goin\u2019 that way.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|title=The Loving Couple|url= https://www.theattic.space/home-page-blogs/2019/11/7/the-loving-couple |website=The Attic|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nTheir families both lived in [[Caroline County, Virginia]]. The county adhered to strict [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow segregation laws]] but Central Point had been a visible mixed-race community since the 19th century.<ref name=\"Staples\"/> Richard's father worked for one of the wealthiest black men in the county for 25 years. Richard's closest companions were black, including those he drag-raced with and Mildred's older brothers. The couple met in high school and fell in love. Richard moved into the Jeter household when Mildred became pregnant.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nAfter the Supreme Court case, the couple moved back to Central Point, where Richard built them a house. The couple had three children: Donald, Peggy, and Sidney.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|title=Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage Dies at 68|author=Douglas Martin|date=May 6, 2008|accessdate=November 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701043346/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|archivedate=July 1, 2017|url-status=live|work=The New York Times|quote=The Lovings' son Donald died in 2000. In addition to her daughter, Peggy Fortune, who lives in Milford, Va., Mrs. Loving is survived by her son, Sidney, of Tappahannock, Va.; eight grandchildren; and 11 great-grandchildren.}}</ref> Richard Loving died aged 41 in 1975, when a drunk driver struck his car in [[Caroline County, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/07/01/archives/richard-p-loving-in-land-mark-suit-figure-in-high-court-ruling-on.html|title=Richard P. Loving; in Landmark Suit; Figure in High Court Ruling on Miscegenation Dies|date=July 1, 1975|work=The New York Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426211818/http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10D13FD3B58157493C3A9178CD85F418785F9|archivedate=April 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Mildred Loving lost her right eye in the same accident. She died of [[pneumonia]] on May 2, 2008, in her home in Central Point, aged 68.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2008|title=died: Mildred Jeter Loving (1939\u20132008)|url=|journal=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education|volume=60|page=83|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Criminal proceedings==\nAt the age of 18, Mildred became pregnant. In June 1958, the couple traveled to [[Washington, D.C.]] to marry, thereby evading Virginia's [[Racial Integrity Act of 1924]], which made marriage between whites and non-whites a crime.<ref>{{cite web|title = Racial Integrity Laws (1924\u20131930)|url = http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Racial_Integrity_Laws_of_the_1920s|website = www.encyclopediavirginia.org|accessdate = 2015-11-04|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151115151130/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/racial_integrity_laws_of_the_1920s|archivedate = 2015-11-15}}</ref> They returned to the small town of [[Central Point, Virginia]]. Based on an anonymous tip,<ref name=NYT>Martin, Douglas. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html \"Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage, Dies at 68\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201080047/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html |date=2016-12-01 }}, ''New York Times'', May 6, 2008.</ref> local police raided their home in the early morning hours of July 11, 1958,<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.biography.com/people/mildred-loving-5884| title =Mildred Loving - Civil Rights Activist - Biography.com| website =[[Biography.com]]| publisher =[[A&E Television Networks, LLC]]| access-date =2017-02-20| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20170211080301/http://www.biography.com/people/mildred-loving-5884| archivedate =2017-02-11}}</ref> hoping to find them having sex, given that interracial sex was then also illegal in Virginia. When the officers found the Lovings sleeping in their bed, Mildred pointed out their marriage certificate on the bedroom wall. They were told the certificate was not valid in Virginia.\n\nThe Lovings were charged under Section 20-58 of the Virginia Code, which prohibited interracial couples from being married out of state and then returning to Virginia, and Section 20\u201359, which classified [[miscegenation]] as a felony, punishable by a prison sentence of between one and five years.\n\nOn January 6, 1959, the Lovings pled guilty to \"cohabiting as man and wife, against the peace and dignity of the Commonwealth\". They were sentenced to one year in prison, with the sentence suspended on condition that the couple leave Virginia and not return together for at least 25 years. After their conviction, the couple moved to the [[District of Columbia]].<ref>''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 3 (\"On January 6, 1959, the Lovings pleaded guilty to the charge and were sentenced to one year in jail; however, the trial judge suspended the sentence for a period of 25 years on the condition that the Lovings leave the State and not return to Virginia together for 25 years&nbsp;... After their convictions, the Lovings took up residence in the District of Columbia.\")</ref>\n\n===Appellate proceedings===\nIn 1964, frustrated by their inability to travel together to visit their families in Virginia, as well as their social isolation and financial difficulties in Washington, Mildred Loving wrote in protest to [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Robert F. Kennedy]].<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/remember-jan-june08-loving_05-06 \"Mildred Loving, Key Figure in Civil Rights Era, Dies\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613230048/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/remember-jan-june08-loving_05-06/ |date=2017-06-13 }}, PBS Online News Hour, May 6, 2008</ref> Kennedy referred her to the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU).<ref name=NYT/> The ACLU assigned volunteer cooperating attorneys [[Bernard S. Cohen]] and [[Philip Hirschkop|Philip J. Hirschkop]], who filed a motion on behalf of the Lovings in the Virginia Caroline County Circuit Court, that requested the court to [[Vacated judgment|vacate]] the criminal judgments and set aside the Lovings' sentences on the grounds that the Virginia miscegenation statutes ran counter to the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]]'s [[Equal Protection Clause]].\n\nOn October 28, 1964, after waiting almost a year for a response to their motion, the ACLU attorneys brought a class action suit in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia. This prompted the county court judge in the case, Leon M. Bazile (1890\u20131967), to issue a ruling on the long-pending motion to vacate. Echoing [[Johann Friedrich Blumenbach]]'s 18th-century interpretation of race, Bazile wrote:\n\n{{quote|Almighty God created the races white, black, yellow, malay and red, and he placed them on separate continents. And but for the interference with his arrangement there would be no cause for such marriages. The fact that he separated the races shows that he did not intend for the races to mix.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opinion of Judge Bazile in Commonwealth v. Loving (January 22, 1965)|url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Opinion_of_Judge_Leon_M_Bazile_January_22_1965|website=www.encyclopediavirginia.org|accessdate=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128135102/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Opinion_of_Judge_Leon_M_Bazile_January_22_1965|archivedate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nOn January 22, 1965, a three-judge district court panel postponed decision on the federal class-action case while the Lovings appealed Judge Bazile's decision on constitutional grounds to the [[Supreme Court of Virginia|Virginia Supreme Court]]. Justice [[Harry L. Carrico]] (later Chief Justice of the Court) wrote an opinion for the court upholding the constitutionality of the anti-miscegenation statutes. While he upheld their criminal convictions, he directed that their sentence be modified.<ref>{{cite web|title = Loving v. Commonwealth (March 7, 1966)|url = http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Commonwealth_March_7_1966|website = www.encyclopediavirginia.org|accessdate = 2015-11-04|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910095234/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Commonwealth_March_7_1966|archivedate = September 10, 2015}}</ref> Carrico cited as authority the Virginia Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Naim v. Naim]]'' (1955) and argued that the Lovings' case was not a violation of the Equal Protection Clause because both the white and the non-white spouse were punished equally for the crime of miscegenation, an argument similar to that made by the United States Supreme Court in 1883 in ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]''.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Loving v. Commonwealth |vol=206 |reporter=Va. |opinion=924 |pinpoint= |court= |date=1966 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/virginia/supreme-court/1966/6163-1.html |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> However, the court did find the Lovings' sentences to be unconstitutionally vague, struck them down, and ordered them resentenced in the Caroline County Circuit Court.\n\nThe Lovings, still supported by the ACLU, appealed the decision to the United States Supreme Court, where Virginia was represented by [[Robert McIlwaine]] of the state's attorney general's office. The Lovings did not attend the oral arguments in Washington,<ref>Kate Sheppard, [https://www.motherjones.com/media/2012/02/the-loving-story-documentary-hbo {{\"'}}The Loving Story': How an Interracial Couple Changed a Nation\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220203224/https://www.motherjones.com/media/2012/02/the-loving-story-documentary-hbo |date=2017-02-20 }}, ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'', Feb 13, 2012.</ref> but one of their lawyers, [[Bernard S. Cohen]], conveyed the message he had been given by Richard Loving: \"Mr. Cohen, tell the Court I love my wife, and it is just unfair that I can't live with her in Virginia.\"<ref name=\"Oyez\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/1966/395|title=Loving v. Virginia oral argument transcript|accessdate=November 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115152456/https://www.oyez.org/cases/1966/395|archivedate=November 15, 2016}} Also quoted in [http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Virginia_1967 Loving v. Virginia (1967)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214144034/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Loving_v_Virginia_1967 |date=2012-12-14 }}, ''[[Encyclopedia Virginia]]''</ref>\n\n==Precedents==\n[[File:US miscegenation.svg|thumb|Date range U.S. states repealed anti-miscegenation laws: {{legend|#d3d3d3|No laws passed}}\n{{legend|#5b9e39|1780 to 1887}}\n{{legend|#f3ee66|1948 to 1967}}\n{{legend|#cc2f2f|After 1967}}]]\nBefore ''Loving v. Virginia'', there had been several cases on the subject of interracial sexual relations. Within the state of Virginia, on October 3, 1878, in ''Kinney v. The Commonwealth'', the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]] ruled that the marriage legalized in [[Washington, D.C.]] between Andrew Kinney, a black man, and Mahala Miller, a white woman, was \"invalid\" in Virginia.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=DeNeen|title=Before Loving v. Virginia, another interracial couple fought in court for their marriage|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/11/before-loving-v-virginia-another-interracial-couple-fought-in-court-for-their-marriage/|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=11 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611132258/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/11/before-loving-v-virginia-another-interracial-couple-fought-in-court-for-their-marriage/|archivedate=11 June 2017|df=mdy}}</ref> In the national case of ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]'' (1883), the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] ruled that the conviction of an Alabama couple for interracial sex, affirmed on appeal by the Alabama Supreme Court, did not violate the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]].<ref name=Pace>{{ussc|name=Pace v. Alabama|volume=106|page=583|year=1883}}</ref> Interracial marital sex was deemed a felony, whereas extramarital sex (\"adultery or fornication\") was only a misdemeanor. On appeal, the United States Supreme Court ruled that the criminalization of interracial sex was not a violation of the [[equal protection clause]] because whites and non-whites were punished in equal measure for the offense of engaging in interracial sex. The court did not need to affirm the constitutionality of the ban on interracial marriage that was also part of Alabama's anti-miscegenation law, since the plaintiff, Mr. Pace, had chosen not to appeal that section of the law. After ''Pace v. Alabama'', the constitutionality of anti-miscegenation laws banning marriage and sex between whites and non-whites remained unchallenged until the 1920s.\n\nIn ''Kirby v. Kirby'' (1921), Mr. Kirby asked the state of Arizona for an annulment of his marriage. He charged that his marriage was invalid because his wife was of \"negro\" descent, thus violating the state's anti-miscegenation law. The Arizona Supreme Court judged Mrs. Kirby's race by observing her physical characteristics and determined that she was of mixed race, therefore granting Mr. Kirby's annulment.<ref name=Pascoe_pp49-51>{{harvnb|Pascoe|1996|pp=49\u201351}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''Monks'' case (''[[Estate of Monks]]'', 4. Civ. 2835, Records of California Court of Appeals, Fourth district), the Superior Court of San Diego County in 1939 decided to invalidate the marriage of Marie Antoinette and Allan Monks because she was deemed to have \"one eighth negro blood\". The court case involved a legal challenge over the conflicting wills that had been left by the late Allan Monks; an old one in favor of a friend named Ida Lee, and a newer one in favor of his wife. Lee's lawyers charged that the marriage of the Monkses, which had taken place in Arizona, was invalid under Arizona state law because Marie Antoinette was \"a Negro\" and Alan had been white. Despite conflicting testimony by various expert witnesses, the judge defined Mrs. Monks' race by relying on the anatomical \"expertise\" of a surgeon. The judge ignored the arguments of an anthropologist and a biologist that it was impossible to tell a person's race from physical characteristics.<ref name=Pascoe_p56>{{harvnb|Pascoe |1996|p=56}}</ref>\n\nMonks then challenged the Arizona anti-miscegenation law itself, taking her case to the California Court of Appeals, Fourth District. Monks' lawyers pointed out that the anti-miscegenation law effectively prohibited Monks as a mixed-race person from marrying anyone: \"As such, she is prohibited from marrying a negro or any descendant of a negro, a Mongolian or an Indian, a Malay or a Hindu, or any descendants of any of them. Likewise&nbsp;... as a descendant of a negro she is prohibited from marrying a Caucasian or a descendant of a Caucasian.&nbsp;...\" The Arizona anti-miscegenation statute thus prohibited Monks from contracting a valid marriage in Arizona, and was therefore an unconstitutional constraint on her liberty. However, the court dismissed this argument as inapplicable, because the case presented involved not two mixed-race spouses but a mixed-race and a white spouse: \"Under the facts presented the appellant does not have the benefit of assailing the validity of the statute.\"<ref name=Pascoe_p60>{{harvnb|Pascoe |1996|p=60}}</ref> Dismissing Monks' appeal in 1942, the United States Supreme Court refused to reopen the issue.\n\nThe turning point came with ''[[Perez v. Sharp]]'' (1948), also known as ''Perez v. Lippold''. In ''Perez'', the [[Supreme Court of California]] recognized that bans on interracial marriage violated the Fourteenth Amendment of the Federal Constitution.\n\n==Supreme Court decision==\nOn June 12, 1967, the Supreme Court issued a unanimous 9\u20130 decision that overturned the Lovings' Virginia criminal convictions and struck down anti-miscegenation laws that forbade marriage between people of different races.\n\nThe Court's opinion was written by [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[Earl Warren]], and all the justices joined it.{{notetag|The decision also includes a very short concurring opinion\u2014only two sentences long\u2014written by Justice [[Potter Stewart]]. Stewart took the position that no state criminal law can be valid \"which makes the criminality  of an act depend upon the race of the actor,\" a standard which reflects Justice [[John Marshall Harlan]]'s dissent in 1896's ''[[Plessy v. Ferguson]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Schoff | first= Rebecca | year=2009 | title = Note: Deciding on Doctrine: Anti-Miscegnation Statutes and the Development of Equal Protection Analysis | url=http://www.virginialawreview.org/volumes/content/deciding-doctrine-anti-miscegenation-statutes-and-development-equal-protection | journal=Virginia Law Review | volume=95 | issue=3 | pages = 627\u201365}}.</ref>}} It began by rejecting Virginia's argument that the anti-miscegenation clause in its Racial Integrity Act did not violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment because the punishment for violating the statute was the same regardless of the offender's race\u2014that is, a white person who married a black person received the same punishment as black person who married a white person\u2014and therefore it \"equally burdened\" both whites and non-whites. The Court had upheld this \"equal burden\" argument 84 years earlier in the 1883 case ''[[Pace v. Alabama]]'', but in ''Loving'' it rejected it and overruled ''Pace'', stating: \"We reject the notion that the mere 'equal application' of a statute concerning racial classifications is enough to remove the classifications from the Fourteenth Amendment's proscription of all invidious racial discriminations.\"<ref>{{harvp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}}, quoting ''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 8.</ref> The Court ruled that because the races of the people involved were the only factors determining whether or not they broke the law, the law was therefore a violation of the Equal Protection Clause.{{sfnp|Nowak|Rotunda|2012|loc=\u00a7 18.28(a), pp. 80\u201381}}\n{{Quote\n|text=There can be no question but that Virginia's miscegenation statutes rest solely upon distinctions drawn according to race. The statutes proscribe generally accepted conduct if engaged in by members of different races. ... There can be no doubt that restricting the freedom to marry solely because of racial classifications violates the central meaning of the Equal Protection Clause.\n|source=''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 11\u201312.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;9.3.1, p. 757}}\n}}\nAfter holding that Virginia's anti-miscegenation law violated the Equal Protection Clause, the Court concluded its opinion with a short section holding that it also violated the Fourteenth Amendment's [[Due Process Clause]], because it deprived its people of a constitutionally protected right without [[due process of law]].{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;10.2.1, p. 863}} It held that the freedom to marry is a fundamental right, and therefore that depriving Americans of this liberty on an arbitrary basis such as race was unconstitutional.{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;10.2.1, p. 863}}\n{{Quote\n|text=The freedom to marry has long been recognized as one of the vital personal rights essential to the orderly pursuit of happiness by free men. Marriage is one of the \"basic civil rights of man,\" fundamental to our very existence and survival. To deny this fundamental freedom on so unsupportable a basis as the racial classifications embodied in these statutes, classifications so directly subversive of the principle of equality at the heart of the Fourteenth Amendment, is surely to deprive all the State's citizens of liberty without due process of law.\n|source=''Loving'', 388 U.S. at 12 (case citations omitted).{{sfnp|Chemerinsky|2019|loc=\u00a7&nbsp;10.2.1, p. 863}}\n}}\n\n==Effects==\n\n===For interracial marriage===\nDespite the Supreme Court's decision, anti-miscegenation laws remained on the books in several states, although the decision had made them unenforceable. Local judges in [[Alabama]] continued to enforce that state's anti-miscegenation statute until the Nixon administration obtained a ruling from a U.S. District Court in ''United States v. Brittain'' in 1970.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=United States v. Brittain |vol=319 |reporter=F. Supp. |opinion=1058 |pinpoint= |court=[[N.D. Ala.]] |date=1970 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/319/1058/2134867/ |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenthal|first1=Jack|title=Government Seeks to Allow A Mixed Marriage in Alabama|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/12/04/355155472.pdf|accessdate=January 25, 2015|work=New York Times|date=December 4, 1970}}</ref> In 2000, Alabama became the last state to adapt its laws to the Supreme Court's decision, when 60% of voters endorsed a [[ballot initiative]] that removed anti-miscegenation language from the state constitution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/weekinreview/november-5-11-marry-at-will.html |title=November 5\u201311; Marry at Will |work=New York Times |date=November 12, 2000 |accessdate=May 27, 2009 |quote=The margin by which the measure passed was itself a statement. A clear majority, 60 percent, voted to remove the miscegenation statute from the state constitution, but 40 percent of Alabamans \u2013 nearly 526,000 people \u2013 voted to keep it. |first=Somini |last=Sengupta |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821110359/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/weekinreview/november-5-11-marry-at-will.html |archivedate=August 21, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Loving v. Virginia'', the number of interracial marriages continued to increase across the United States<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/18090277 |title=Interracial marriage flourishes in U.S. |publisher=NBC News |date=April 15, 2007 |accessdate=December 13, 2012 }}</ref> and in the South. In Georgia, for instance, the number of interracial marriages increased from 21 in 1967 to 115 in 1970.<ref>Aldridge, ''The Changing Nature of Interracial Marriage in Georgia: A Research Note'', 1973</ref> At the national level, 0.4% of marriages were interracial in 1960, 2.0% in 1980,<ref name=\"UnitedStatesCensusData\">{{cite web| url =https://www.census.gov/population/socdemo/race/interractab1.txt| title =Table 1. Race of Wife by Race of Husband: 1960, 1970, 1980, 1991, and 1992| date =1994-07-05| website =[[census.gov]]| publisher =[[U.S. Bureau of the Census]]| access-date =2017-02-20| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20170304155503/https://www.census.gov/population/socdemo/race/interractab1.txt| archivedate =2017-03-04}}</ref> 12% in 2013,<ref>{{cite web|title=Interracial marriage: Who is 'marrying out'?|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/06/12/interracial-marriage-who-is-marrying-out/|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|accessdate=11 August 2016|date=12 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812004242/http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/06/12/interracial-marriage-who-is-marrying-out/|archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> and 16% in 2015, almost 50 years after ''Loving''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Intermarriage across the U.S. by metro area|url=http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/interactives/intermarriage-across-the-u-s-by-metro-area/|website=Pew Research Center's Social & Demographic Trends Project|accessdate=11 June 2017|date=18 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606132122/http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/interactives/intermarriage-across-the-u-s-by-metro-area/|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===For same-sex marriage===\n''Loving v. Virginia'' was discussed in the context of the public debate about [[same-sex marriage in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Trei |first=Lisa |url=http://news.stanford.edu/pr/2007/pr-rosenfeld-061307.html |title=''Loving v. Virginia'' provides roadmap for same-sex marriage advocates |publisher=News.stanford.edu |date=June 13, 2007 |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213011039/http://news.stanford.edu/pr/2007/pr-rosenfeld-061307.html |archivedate=December 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Hern\u00e1ndez v. Robles|Hernandez v. Robles]]'' (2006), the majority opinion of the [[New York Court of Appeals]]\u2014that state's highest court\u2014declined to rely on the ''Loving'' case when deciding whether a right to same-sex marriage existed, holding that \"the historical background of ''Loving'' is different from the history underlying this case.\"<ref name=\"hernandezvrobles\">{{cite court |litigants=Hernandez v. Robles |vol=855 |reporter=N.E.3d |opinion=1 |pinpoint= |court=N.Y. |date=2006 |url=http://www.courts.state.ny.us/reporter/3dseries/2006/2006_05239.htm |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> In the 2010 federal district court decision in ''[[Perry v. Schwarzenegger]]'', overturning [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|California's Proposition 8]] which restricted marriage to opposite-sex couples, Judge [[Vaughn R. Walker]] cited ''Loving v. Virginia'' to conclude that \"the [constitutional] right to marry protects an individual's choice of marital partner regardless of gender\".<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Perry v. Schwarzenegger |vol=704 |reporter=F. Supp. 2d |opinion=921 |pinpoint= |court=[[N.D. Cal.]] |date=2010 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20101015624 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> On narrower grounds, the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/08/us/marriage-ban-violates-constitution-court-rules.html |first1=Adam |last1=Nagoruney |date=February 7, 2012 |title=Court Strikes Down Ban on Gay Marriage in California |work=New York Times |accessdate=February 8, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211122706/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/08/us/marriage-ban-violates-constitution-court-rules.html |archivedate=February 11, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"9th\">{{cite court |litigants=Perry v. Brown |vol=671 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1052 |pinpoint= |court=[[9th Cir.]] |date=2012 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120207000t |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, on the 40th anniversary of the Supreme Court's decision in ''Loving'', Mildred Loving issued the following statement:\n{{quote|My generation was bitterly divided over something that should have been so clear and right. The majority believed that what the judge said, that it was God's plan to keep people apart, and that government should discriminate against people in love. But I have lived long enough now to see big changes. The older generation's fears and prejudices have given way, and today's young people realize that if someone loves someone they have a right to marry.\n\nSurrounded as I am now by wonderful children and grandchildren, not a day goes by that I don't think of Richard and our love, our right to marry, and how much it meant to me to have that freedom to marry the person precious to me, even if others thought he was the \"wrong kind of person\" for me to marry. I believe all Americans, no matter their race, no matter their sex, no matter their sexual orientation, should have that same freedom to marry. Government has no business imposing some people's religious beliefs over others. Especially if it denies people's civil rights.\n\nI am still not a political person, but I am proud that Richard's and my name is on a court case that can help reinforce the love, the commitment, the fairness, and the family that so many people, black or white, young or old, gay or straight seek in life. I support the freedom to marry for all. That's what Loving, and loving, are all about.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/acsblog/mildred-loving-endorses-marriage-equality-for-same-sex-couples/|title=Mildred Loving Endorses Marriage Equality for Same-Sex Couples|publisher=[[American Constitution Society]]|date=June 15, 2007|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/daily-dish/archive/2007/06/mildred-loving-40-years-later/227582/|title=Mildred Loving, 40 Years Later|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=June 18, 2007|accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|title=Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage, Dies at 68|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=May 6, 2008|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nUp until 2014, five [[United States court of appeals|U.S. Courts of Appeals]] considered the constitutionality of state bans on same-sex marriage. In doing so they interpreted or used the ''Loving'' ruling differently:\n\n*The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Fourth]] and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit|Tenth]] Circuits used ''Loving'' along with other cases like ''[[Zablocki v. Redhail]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Zablocki v. Redhail|volume=434|page=374|pin=|year=1978}}</ref> and ''[[Turner v. Safley]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Turner v. Safley|volume=482|page=78|pin=|year=1987}}</ref> to demonstrate that the U.S. Supreme Court has recognized a \"fundamental right to marry\" that a state cannot restrict unless it meets the court's \"[[heightened scrutiny]]\" standard. Using that standard, both courts struck down state bans on same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Bostic v. Shaefer |vol=760 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=352 |pinpoint=376 |court=[[4th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20140728145 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=Perhaps most notably, in ''Loving v. Virginia'', the Supreme Court invalidated a Virginia law that prohibited white individuals from marrying individuals of other races. The Court explained that '[t]he freedom to marry has long been recognized as one of the vital personal rights essential to the orderly pursuit of happiness by free men' and that no valid basis justified the Virginia law's infringement of that right. [citations omitted]}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants=Kitchen v. Herbert |vol=755 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1193 |pinpoint= |court=[[10th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20140625074 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref>\n*Two other courts of appeals, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|Seventh]] and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth]] Circuits, struck down state bans on the basis of a different line of argument. Instead of \"fundamental rights\" analysis, they reviewed bans on same-sex marriage as discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation. The former cited ''Loving'' to demonstrate that the Supreme Court did not accept tradition as a justification for limiting access to marriage.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Baskin v. Bogan |vol=766 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=648 |pinpoint= |court=[[7th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20140904126 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref> The latter cited ''Loving'' as quoted in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'' on the question of federalism: \"state laws defining or regulating marriage, of course, must respect the constitutional rights of persons\".<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Latta v. Otter |vol=771 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=456 |pinpoint=474 |court= |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20141007102 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=}}</ref>\n*The only Court of Appeals to uphold state bans on same-sex marriage, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|Sixth Circuit]], said that when the ''Loving'' decision discussed marriage it was referring only to marriage between persons of the opposite sex.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=DeBoer v. Snyder |vol=772 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=388 |pinpoint=411 |court=[[6th Cir.]] |date=2014 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20141106144 |accessdate=2018-07-26 |quote=Matters do not change because ''Loving v. Virginia'' held that 'marriage' amounts to a fundamental right.&nbsp;... In referring to 'marriage' rather than \"opposite-sex marriage\", ''Loving'' confirmed only that 'opposite-sex marriage' would have been considered redundant, not that marriage included same-sex couples. ''Loving'' did not change the definition. [citations omitted]}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' (2015), the Supreme Court invoked ''Loving'', among other cases, as precedent for its holding that states are required to allow same-sex marriages under both the Equal Protection Clause and the Due Process Clause of the Constitution.<ref name=Obergefell/> The court's decision in ''Obergefell'' cited ''Loving'' nearly a dozen times, and was based on the same principles \u2013 equality and an [[unenumerated right]] to marriage. During oral argument, the eventual author of the majority opinion, Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]], noted that the ruling holding racial segregation unconstitutional and the ruling holding bans on interracial marriage unconstitutional (''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]'' in 1954 and ''Loving v. Virginia'' in 1967, respectively) were made about 13 years apart, much like the ruling holding bans on same-sex sexual activity unconstitutional and the eventual ruling holding bans on same-sex marriage unconstitutional (''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'' in 2003 and ''Obergefell v. Hodges'' in 2015, respectively).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Amar|first1=Akhil Reed|title=Anthony Kennedy and the Ghost of Earl Warren|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2015/07/06/obergefell_v_hodges_anthony_kennedy_continues_the_legacy_of_earl_warren.html|accessdate=6 July 2015|work=Slate|date=6 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707032841/http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2015/07/06/obergefell_v_hodges_anthony_kennedy_continues_the_legacy_of_earl_warren.html|archivedate=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Remembrance and representation in popular culture==\n[[File:Graves of Mildred and Richard Loving.jpg|thumb|Graves of the Lovings in the St. Stephen's Baptist Church cemetery, Central Point]]\nIn the United States, June 12, the date of the decision, has become known as [[Loving Day]], an annual unofficial celebration of interracial marriages. In 2014, Mildred Loving was honored as one of the [[Library of Virginia]]'s \"[[Virginia Women in History]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lva.virginia.gov/public/vawomen/2014/honoree.htm?bio=Loving|title=Virginia Women in History: Mildred Delores Jeter Loving|publisher=Library of Virginia|accessdate=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321185328/http://www.lva.virginia.gov/public/vawomen/2014/honoree.htm?bio=Loving|archivedate=21 March 2015}}</ref> In 2017, the [[Virginia Department of Historic Resources]] dedicated a state [[historical marker]], which tells the story of the Lovings, outside the [[Patrick Henry Building]] in Richmond \u2013  the former site of the [[Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Virginia to honor interracial marriage with state historical marker|url=http://wtvr.com/2017/06/08/interracial-marriage-historical-marker/|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=WTVR.com|date=8 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608185356/http://wtvr.com/2017/06/08/interracial-marriage-historical-marker/|archivedate=8 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe story of the Lovings became the basis of several films:\n* The first, ''[[Mr. and Mrs. Loving]]'' (1996), was written and directed by [[Richard Friedenberg]] and starred [[Lela Rochon]], [[Timothy Hutton]], and [[Ruby Dee]].<ref>*{{IMDb title|id=0117098|title=Mr. & Mrs. Loving}}</ref> According to Mildred Loving, \"not much of it was very true. The only part of it right was I had three children.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Dionne Walker|publisher=USAToday.com|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-06-10-loving_N.htm|title=Pioneer of interracial marriage looks back|date=June 10, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509035254/http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-06-10-loving_N.htm|archivedate=May 9, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"iht\">{{cite news | title=40 years of interracial marriage: Mildred Loving reflects on breaking the color barrier | agency=Associated Press | work=[[International Herald-Tribune]] | date=June 9, 2007 | accessdate=April 28, 2008 | url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/10/america/NA-FEA-GEN-US-Loving-Anniversary.php | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508202344/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/10/america/NA-FEA-GEN-US-Loving-Anniversary.php | archivedate=May 8, 2008 }}</ref> \n* The second film, Nancy Buirski's documentary ''The Loving Story,'' premiered on [[HBO]] in February 2012<ref name=\"lovings-hbo\">{{cite news|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/arts/television/the-loving-story-an-hbo-documentary.html|title=Scenes From a Marriage That Segregationists Tried to Break Up|first=Alessandra|last=Stanley|date=February 13, 2012|work=New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214075848/http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/arts/television/the-loving-story-an-hbo-documentary.html|archivedate=February 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://icarusfilms.com/new2012/ls.html The Loving Story] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612142413/http://icarusfilms.com/new2012/ls.html |date=2012-06-12 }}, accessed March 25, 2015</ref> and won a [[Peabody Award]] that year.<ref>[http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/the-loving-story 72nd Annual Peabody Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911220051/http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/the-loving-story |date=2014-09-11 }}, May 2013.</ref>\n* A third film, ''[[Loving (2016 film)|Loving]]'', was released in 2016, directed by [[Jeff Nichols]] and starring [[Ruth Negga]] and [[Joel Edgerton]] as the Lovings. The film is based on Buirski's documentary. Negga received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for her performance.\n* A four-part film, ''The Loving Generation'', premiered on [[First Look Media|Topic.com]] in February 2018. Directed and produced by [[Lacey Schwartz]] and Mehret Mandefro, it explores the lives of biracial children born after the ''Loving'' decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.topic.com/the-loving-generation |title=The Loving Generation |publisher=[[First Look Media|Topic.com]] |accessdate=February 18, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217162449/https://www.topic.com/the-loving-generation |archivedate=February 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theroot.com/the-loving-generation-explores-the-lives-of-biracial-ch-1822767412|title=The Loving Generation Explores the Lives of Biracial Children Born After Mixed-Race Marriages Were Legalized|last=Branigin|first=Anne|date=February 10, 2018|work=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]|access-date=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216030806/https://www.theroot.com/the-loving-generation-explores-the-lives-of-biracial-ch-1822767412|archivedate=February 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/10/opinion/sunday/black-with-some-white-privilege.html|title=Black With (Some) White Privilege|last=Holmes|first=Anna|authorlink=Anna Holmes|date=February 10, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214184644/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/10/opinion/sunday/black-with-some-white-privilege.html|archivedate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn music, [[Nanci Griffith]]'s 2009 album ''[[The Loving Kind (Nanci Griffith album)|The Loving Kind]]'' is named for the Lovings and includes a song about them. [[Roy Zimmerman (satirist)|Satirist Roy Zimmerman]]'s 2009 song ''The Summer of Loving''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xQWrasoNS24 |title=\"Summer of Loving\" - Roy Zimmerman |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-06-11 |accessdate=2019-04-05}}</ref> is about the Lovings and their 1967 case, making reference to the hippies' \"[[Summer of Love]]\" of that same year.\n\nA 2015 novel by the French journalist Gilles Biassette, ''L'amour des Loving'' (\"The Love of the Lovings\", {{ISBN|978-2917559598}}), recounts the life of the Lovings and their case.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mahuzier|first1=Marc|title=L'amour en noir et blanc|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/lamour-en-noir-et-blanc-3498156|accessdate=22 June 2015|work=[[Ouest-France]]|date=21 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924160041/http://www.ouest-france.fr/lamour-en-noir-et-blanc-3498156|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref> A [[photo-essay]] about the couple by Grey Villet, created just before the case, was republished in 2017.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Villet|first1=Barbara|last2=Villet|first2=Grey|title=The Lovings: An Intimate Portrait|date=February 14, 2017|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=978-1616895563}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{notefoot}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* {{cite book | first=Erwin | last=Chemerinsky | title=Constitutional Law: Principles and Policies | edition= 6th | location=New York | publisher=Wolters Kluwer | year=2019 | isbn=978-1-4548-9574-9 | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book | first1=John E. | last1=Nowak | first2=Ronald D. | last2=Rotunda | title=Treatise on Constitutional Law: Substance and Procedure | year=2012 | location=Eagan, Minnesota | publisher=West Thomson/Reuters| edition= 5th | oclc = 798148265 | ref=harv}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Aldridge |first=Delores |title=The Changing Nature of Interracial Marriage in Georgia: A Research Note |journal=Journal of Marriage and the Family |volume=35 |issue=4 |year=1973 |pages=641\u2013642 |doi=10.2307/350877 |jstor=350877 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Annella |first